#compdef systemd-storagetm
# Documentation: source-direct extraction from upstream
# systemd/systemd src/storagetm/storagetm.c —
#   parse_argv() at lines 76-145 (OptionParser FOREACH_OPTION_
#     OR_RETURN dispatch + OPTION_LONG + OPTION entries)
#   --all double-application logic at line 875 (--all twice
#     allows exposing even the root fs)
#   NQN auto-generation at lines 132-141 (NVMe Qualified Name
#     defaults to "nqn.2023-10.io.systemd:storagetm.<machine-id>")
# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# systemd-storagetm is the **NVMe-over-TCP target manager**
# — exposes one or more local block devices over the network
# as NVMe namespaces (using the kernel's nvmet_tcp target
# driver), turning the host into an NVMe-oF target server.
# Used in the systemd Storage Target Mode boot scenario
# (`systemd.storagetm.devices=` kernel cmdline) so the user
# can boot a machine into "expose disks over network" mode for
# disaster recovery or remote provisioning workflows.
#
# Critical extraction note: storagetm uses the modern
# OptionParser idiom (same as R218/R219/R220).  Only 3
# flag-related options:
#   --nqn=STRING      (OPTION_LONG)
#   -a/--all          (OPTION with both short+long)
#   --list-devices    (OPTION_LONG with NO_ARG; early-returns
#                      after printing block device list)
# All other positional args are block device paths.
#
# Critical extraction note: `-a`/`--all` is a SPECIAL increment
# counter (`arg_all++` at line 103) — passing it TWICE
# (`-a -a`) sets the value to 2, which UNLOCKS the root fs
# exposure at line 875 (`if (arg_all >= 2)`).  This is a
# safety interlock to prevent accidental root-fs exposure
# over NVMe-oF.  Documented in completion description.

_arguments -s -S \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help and exit]' \
  '--version[show package version and exit]' \
  '--nqn=[NQN (NVMe Qualified Name) for the target subsystem (default: nqn.2023-10.io.systemd:storagetm.<machine-id>)]:nqn:' \
  '(-a --all)*'{-a,--all}'[expose all devices (pass TWICE to also expose the root fs!)]' \
  '--list-devices[list candidate block devices to operate on, then exit]' \
  '*:block device path (mutex with --all):_files -g "/dev/*"'
